Solid Priorities for Fragile States
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared by the aftermath of the COVID-19 pandemic.
However, the world's most "fragile" states face a particularly complex set of challenges.
In fact, before the pandemic began, countries such as Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and others were already grappling with poverty, conflicts, corruption, and poor public administration.
Today, these issues leave these countries ill-equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
Ce dont chaque pays a besoin afin de traverser la pandémie est précisément ce qu’il manque aux États fragiles : un appareil d’État en mesure d’élaborer et de mettre en œuvre un plan d’action, un corps de police efficace pour faire appliquer les règles, des programmes sociaux qui fournissent des fonds, de l’approvisionnement ainsi que des services de santé pour soigner les personnes infectées.
Le manque de moyens de l’État se fait immédiatement sentir dans le domaine de la santé publique.
Alors que l’Europe compte 4 000 lits aux soins intensifs par million d’habitants, plusieurs régions d’Afrique n’en ont que cinq par million d’habitants.
Le Mali possède seulement trois ventilateurs pour l’ensemble du pays.
Une riposte efficace passe également par la confiance dans l’intervention de l’État.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states does not enjoy much popular support.
In countries emerging from conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, many people will refrain from supporting the government even if it turns out to be capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families, and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to help those who cannot.
However, in fragile states, the official economy is not sufficiently present to meet these needs.
Earlier during the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to the demographic weight of young people and their geographic remoteness.
However, from our perspective as co-presidents of the new Council on State Fragility, it must be acknowledged that this was not the case.
In recent weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all had infection and mortality rates comparable to those of developed countries first hit by the coronavirus.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will likely be more severe for fragile states. These will not only be the result of national lockdowns, but also of what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has been precarious, remittances from expatriates have fallen, basic commodity prices and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are accumulating.
Since fragile states rely on imports for the major part of their food supply, we increasingly speak of "hunger" and even of "famine".
We should now have understood that the problems of less affluent countries become most often global problems whether in the form of massive migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the impoverished populations will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will only worsen.
This is why the Council on State Fragility has made it its absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges these countries must overcome.
The council, composed of former world leaders, ministers, diplomats, business personalities, academics, as well as heads of development organizations, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its aim will be to guide national and international policymakers who will determine how fragile states will emerge from this crisis and address their broader and deeper issues.
The decentralization, adaptability, and smart use of data will be essentials.
For example, it is widely proven that targeted 'confinement' of local outbreaks is often more appropriate than national confinement.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
However, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency dissipates.
We propose five recommendations.
Firstly, access to social protection must be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, this will mean universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile telecommunications networks should be used to gather information on immediate needs and to make small regular payments (although of limited duration).
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which cultivated rice, has become increasingly dependent in recent decades.
Generally speaking, Africa has 60% of the world's unused arable land.
Local initiatives to produce basic crops must be rapidly scaled up to a much greater extent.
Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production begins, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe until all are.
We must advocate for and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, fragile states' businesses need immediate assistance.
As observed by the financial institutions most involved in international development; small enterprises in less affluent countries are often neglected and suffer the adverse consequences of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in large-scale projects in larger economies).
Yet, precisely these small enterprises are the ones that need larger investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is anticipated that countries receiving bilateral development aid will have to repay around 40 billion dollars to private and public creditors this year alone.
To prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to pause accumulated debts not only until next year but also until the end of the crisis.
In addition, it is crucial that all fragile states obtain emergency financing to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions—particularly those countries that do not usually have access to funding from the World Bank or International Monetary Fund.
COVID-19 will exacerbate already existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community reacts quickly, we can mitigate the worst effects of the pandemic.
If there is one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
